Known cut features:
Dealing with locations

User table metadata: create table user ( ID int NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT, email VARCHAR(100), salt VARCHAR(12), password VARCHAR(32), created DATETIME, PRIMARY KEY (ID) )

Location
name(varchar(50)) x(int) y(int) width(int) height(int)

explanation:
Should check the map for proper locations

Item 
id(int) location(varchar(50)) name(varchar(50)) sell(int) cost(int) use(bool) affect(int) attributes(SEE FROM HOME) level(int)

explanation:
location -> id from the table Locations

use true  -> usable item => dont look for attributes
use false -> equiptment  => dont look for affect

affect  11 -> cure poison
		12 -> cure stone
		13 -> HP+
		14 -> HP++
		15 -> HP+++ MP+
		
		23 -> HP+, all party
		24 -> HP++, all party
		25 -> HP+++ MP+, all party
		
Spell
id(int) creatureId(int) location(varchar(50)) name(varchar(50)) sell(int) cost(int) white(bool) level(int) type(varchar(10)) all(bool) applyOn(bool) 
		//affect(HP1, HP2, HP+++, DMG+, DMG++, Stone, Life, Defense, )
		hp(int) -> For example hp(30) means give 30 hp to charecter, but hp(-100) means make 100 dmg do character. If the spell dosn't do anything with
		the hp of the character then it should be hp(0) coz in the game logic I will sum every property with the character properties.
		stone(int) -> if the spell is Stone it will be stone(1) and every other property (hp, atk, def ... ) will be 0.
		Continue like this from HOME.

creatureId means tha creature that can use this spell

level { 1, 2, ... 8 }

applyOn 0 -> enemy
applyOn 1 -> self


type { earth, fire, water, wind, holy, dark }

if(white) -> white magic
else	  -> black magic


   if all -> apply to all units
   else -> apply to selected unit

Connection Tables
	User Item
	userId(int) itemId(int) quantity(int)
	
	User Spell
	userId(int) spellId(int)
	
Creature
id(int) location(varchar(50)) name(varchar(50)) type(varchar(10)) attributes: dmg, atk, def, ... They all should level as the players level








